<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK1">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK6">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<FONT STYLE="BACKGROUND-COLOR:#FFFFFF">
<B>
	Item 7. &nbsp;Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK58">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK57">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Overview
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We are a leading manufacturer of a variety of products and services for diverse commercial and industrial markets. &nbsp;We have five reportable segments: Food Service Equipment, Engraving, Engineering Technologies, Electronics, and the Hydraulics.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our long term strategy is to build larger industrial platforms through a value creation system that assists management in meeting specific corporate and business unit financial and strategic performance goals in order to create, improve, and enhance shareholder value. &nbsp;The Standex Value Creation System is a standard methodology which provides consistent tools used throughout the company in order to achieve our organization&#146;s goals. &nbsp;The value creation system has four components. &nbsp;The Balanced Performance Plan process aligns annual goals throughout the business and provides a standard reporting, management and review process. &nbsp;It is focused on setting and meeting annual and quarterly targets that support our short term and long term goals. &nbsp;&nbsp;The Standex Growth Disciplines use a set of tools and processes including market maps, growth lane ways, and market tests to identify opportunities to expand the business organically and through acquisitions. &nbsp;Standex Operational Excellence employs a standard playbook and processes, including LEAN, to eliminate waste and improve profitability, cash flow and customer satisfaction. &nbsp;Finally, the Standex Talent Management process is an organizational development process that provides training, development, and succession planning for our employees throughout our worldwide organization. &nbsp;The Standex Value Creation System ties all disciplines in the organization together under a common umbrella by providing standard tools and processes to deliver our business objectives:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	It is our objective to grow larger and more profitable business units through both organic initiatives and acquisitions. &nbsp;On an ongoing basis we identify and implement organic growth initiatives such as new product development, geographic expansion, introduction of products and technologies into new markets and applications, key accounts and strategic sales channel partners. &nbsp;Also, we have a long-term objective to create sizable business platforms by adding strategically aligned or &#147;bolt on&#148; acquisitions to strengthen the individual businesses, create both sales and cost synergies with our core business platforms, and accelerate their growth and margin improvement. &nbsp;We have a particular focus on identifying and investing in opportunities that complement our products and will increase the global presence and capabilities of our businesses. &nbsp;From time to time we have divested and likely will continue to divest businesses that we feel are not strategic or do not meet our growth and return expectations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As part of this ongoing strategy, during fiscal year 2016, we acquired Northlake Engineering, Inc., a designer, manufacturer and distributor of high reliability magnetics serving the North American power distribution and medical equipment markets. &nbsp;This investment complements our Electronics segment and allows us to provide broader solutions to our customers. &nbsp;Subsequent to our fiscal 2016 year-end, we sold our U.S. Roll Plate and Machinery business as it was not strategic, and did not meet our growth and return expectations. &nbsp;&nbsp;This divestiture also allows our Engraving management to focus on higher growth and better return businesses within the segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We create &#147;Customer Intimacy&#148; by utilizing the Standex Growth Disciplines to partner with our customers in order to develop and deliver custom solutions or engineered components that provide technology-driven solutions to our customers. &nbsp;This relationship generally provides us with the ability to improve sales and profit growth over time and provide operating margins that enhance shareholder returns. &nbsp;Further, we have made a priority of developing new sales channels and leveraging strategic customer relationships.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Standex Operational Excellence drives continuous improvement in the efficiency of our businesses. &nbsp;We recognize that our businesses are competing in a global economy that requires us to improve our competitive position. &nbsp;We have deployed a number of management competencies to drive improvements in cost structure of our business units including operational excellence through lean enterprise, the use of low cost manufacturing facilities in countries such as Mexico, and China, the consolidation of manufacturing facilities to achieve economies of scale and leveraging of fixed infrastructure costs, alternate sourcing to achieve procurement cost reductions, and capital improvements to increase shop floor productivity.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company&#146;s strong historical cash flow has been a cornerstone for funding our capital allocation strategy. &nbsp;We use cash flow generated from operations to fund the strategic growth programs described above, (including acquisitions and investments for organic growth), and to return cash to our shareholders through payment of dividends and stock buybacks.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our business units are actively engaged in initiating new product introductions, expansion of product offerings through private labeling and sourcing agreements, geographic expansion of sales coverage, the development of new sales channels, leveraging strategic customer relationships, development of energy efficient products, new applications for existing products and technologies, and next generation products and services for our end-user markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restructuring expenses reflect costs associated with the Company&#146;s efforts to continuously improve operational efficiency and expand globally in order to remain competitive in the end-user markets we serve. &nbsp;Each year the Company incurs costs for actions to size its businesses to a level appropriate for current economic conditions and to improve its cost structure to enhance our competitive position and operating margins. &nbsp;Such expenses include costs for moving facilities to low-cost locations, starting up plants after relocation, or downsizing operations because of changing economic conditions, and other costs resulting from asset redeployment decisions. Shutdown costs include severance, benefits, stay bonuses, lease and contract terminations, asset write-downs, costs of moving fixed assets, moving, and relocation costs. &nbsp;Vacant facility costs include maintenance, utilities, property taxes, and other costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We continue to focus on our efforts to reduce cost and improve productivity across our businesses. &nbsp;Our refrigeration division and businesses that serve the oil and gas industry have both been negatively impacted by reduced customer spending and customer consolidation. &nbsp;Due to these changing market conditions and consolidations we have and will continue to implement appropriate cost reductions to align our costs to appropriate sales levels. &nbsp;We continue to evaluate our products and production processes and expect to execute similar cost reductions and restructuring programs on an ongoing basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Because of the diversity of the Company&#146;s businesses, end user markets and geographic locations, management does not use specific external indices to predict the future performance of the Company, other than general information about broad macroeconomic trends. &nbsp;Each of our individual business units serves niche markets and attempts to identify trends other than general business and economic conditions which are specific to their businesses and which could impact their performance. &nbsp;Those units report pertinent information to senior management, which uses it to the extent relevant to assess the future performance of the Company. &nbsp;A description of any such material trends is described below in the applicable segment analysis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We monitor a number of key performance indicators (&#147;KPIs&#148;) including net sales, income from operations, backlog, effective income tax rate, gross profit margin, and operating cash flow. &nbsp;A discussion of these KPIs is included in the discussion below. &nbsp;We may also supplement the discussion of these KPIs by identifying the impact of foreign exchange rates, acquisitions, and other significant items when they have a material impact on the discussed KPI. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We believe that the discussion of these items provides enhanced information to investors by disclosing their consequence on the overall trend in order to provide a clearer comparative view of the KPI where applicable. &nbsp;For discussion of the impact of foreign exchange rates on KPIs, the Company calculates the impact as the difference between the current period KPI calculated at the current period exchange rate as compared to the KPI calculated at the historical exchange rate for the prior period. &nbsp;For discussion of the impact of acquisitions, we isolate the effect to the KPI amount that would have existed regardless of our acquisition. &nbsp;Sales resulting from synergies between the acquisition and existing operations of the Company are considered organic growth for the purposes of our discussion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Unless otherwise noted, references to years are to fiscal years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

	Consolidated Results from Continuing Operations (in thousands):
</B>
</P>

</P>

<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=112>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=RIGHT>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3,954
</P>

<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=266.8>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Organic sales growth
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=17.2>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" WIDTH=102>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=RIGHT>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(17,217)
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=15.733>

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=RIGHT>
	34,230
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=15.733>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=112>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=RIGHT>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;38,539
</P>
</TD>

</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales for the fiscal year 2016 decreased by $20.6 million, or 2.7%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The decrease is driven by $17.2 million, or 2.3% of organic sales declines and $15.0 million, or 1.9%, of unfavorable foreign exchange partially offset by $11.7 million, or 1.5% from the Northlake and Enginetics acquisitions. &nbsp;The organic sales decrease was primarily driven by lower sales to the refrigeration and oil and gas markets, partially offset by higher sales to the automotive and other markets. &nbsp;We anticipate continued soft demand in the refrigeration and oil and gas markets during the first half of fiscal year 2017. &nbsp;We expect unfavorable foreign exchange sales impacts in 2017 primarily associated with declines in the British Pound due to the Brexit vote. &nbsp;During fiscal year 2016, 3.0% of our consolidated revenue was recorded in the U.K. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales for the fiscal year 2015 increased by $56.0 million, or 7.8%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The increase was driven by $34.2 million or 4.8% of organic sales growth from three of our segments, $38.2 million or 5.3% of acquisitions from Enginetics, Ultrafryer, and Planar partially offset by unfavorable foreign exchange of $16.4 million or 2.3% primarily from the strength of the U.S. dollar as compared to the Euro and Pound. &nbsp;Sales growth was a result of success of our top-line growth initiatives and improvements in end-user markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Gross Profit Margin
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During 2016, gross margin increased to 33.6% as compared to 32.1% in 2015. &nbsp;The increase is a result of higher sales in the Engraving segment which typically carry higher margins than sales in our other segments and operational improvements in our Food Service Equipment segment as our Operational Excellence initiatives continue to generate positive gross margin results. &nbsp;We also experienced gross margin improvements due to reduced purchase accounting charges of $1.3 million. &nbsp;During fiscal year 2016 we incurred $0.4 million of purchase accounting charges related to the Northlake acquisition as compared to charges of $1.7 million in the prior year for the Enginetics and Ultrafryer acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During 2015, gross margin decreased to 32.1% as compared to 33.3% in 2014. &nbsp;This decrease is primarily a result of exchange rate declines, an unfavorable sales mix as compared to the prior year, coupled with $1.7 million of purchase accounting charges associated with the Enginetics and Ultrafryer acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Selling, General, and Administrative Expenses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Selling, general, and administrative expenses, (&#147;SG&amp;A&#148;) for the fiscal year 2016 were $170.2 million or 22.6% of sales compared to $165.8 million or 21.5% of sales during the prior year. &nbsp;The increase in SG&amp;A is due to higher health care expenses, compensation, along with SG&amp;A embedded in the Northlake business partially offset by declines in distribution expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Selling, general, and administrative expenses, (&#147;SG&amp;A&#148;) for the fiscal year 2015 were $165.8 million or 21.5% of sales compared to $165.8 million or 23.1% of sales during the prior year. &nbsp;The decline in SG&amp;A as a percentage of sales relates to three primary items: the absence of $3.9 million of management transition costs in 2014; increased selling and distribution expense in the then current year associated with a 4.8% increase in organic sales during the year; and $6.6 million of incremental expenses as a result of the Ultrafryer and Enginetics acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Income from Operations
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations for the fiscal year 2016 decreased by $8.3 million or 10.6%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The decrease is a result of a $7.3 million non-cash loss incurred to adjust the net realizable value of the Roll Plate and Machinery business, increases in health care and compensation expenses, partially offset by gross profit improvements as a result of business segment mix. &nbsp;Discussion of the performance of all of our reportable segments is more fully explained in the segment analysis that follows. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations for the fiscal year 2015 increased by $12.8 million or 19.4%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The increase was primarily driven by $56.0 million of sales increases, increasing gross profit by $9.2 million, along with a $6.6 million decline in restructuring expenses, and a reduction in net gain from insurance proceeds of $3.0 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Interest Expense
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Interest expense for the fiscal year 2016 was $2.9 million, a decrease of $0.3 million as compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The decrease is primarily due to lower average borrowings outstanding during the year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Interest expense for the fiscal year 2015 was $3.2 million, an increase of $0.9 million as compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The increase is primarily due to higher average borrowings outstanding during the year as a result of the Enginetics acquisition and increased capital spending to support strategic growth programs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2016 was $16.3 million, or an effective rate of 23.8%, compared to $20.9 million, or an effective rate of 27.4% for the year ended June 30, 2015. &nbsp;Changes in the effective tax rates from period to period may be significant as they depend on many factors including, but not limited to, the amount of the Company's income or loss, the mix of income earned in the US versus outside the US, the effective tax rate in each of the countries in which we earn income, and any one time tax issues which occur during the period. &nbsp;We anticipate our tax rate will be approximately 28% in the coming fiscal year due to mix of income earned in jurisdictions with higher tax rates. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2016 was impacted by the following items: (i) a benefit of $4.9 million due to the mix of income earned in jurisdictions with beneficial tax rates, (ii) a net benefit of $0.9 million related to a bargain-sale of idle property to a charitable organization, and (iii) a benefit of $0.7 million related to the R&amp;D tax credit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2015 was $20.9 million, an effective rate of 27.4%, compared to $18.1 million, an effective rate of 26.6% for the year ended June 30, 2014. &nbsp;The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2015 was impacted by the following items: (i) a benefit of $0.5 million related to the R&amp;D tax credit that expired during the fiscal year on December 31, 2014 (ii) a benefit of $4.0 million due to the mix of income earned in jurisdictions with beneficial tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2014 was impacted by the following items: (i) a benefit of $0.5 million related to the R&amp;D tax credit that expired during the fiscal year on December 31, (ii) a benefit of $0.5 million related to a decrease in the statutory tax rate in the United Kingdom on prior period deferred tax liabilities recorded during the first quarter during the fiscal year, (iii) a benefit of $1.1 million due to non-taxable life insurance proceeds received in the third quarter and (iv) a benefit of $3.8 million due to the mix of income earned in jurisdictions with beneficial tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Capital Expenditures
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In general, our capital expenditures over the long term are expected to be approximately 2% to 3% of net sales. &nbsp;During 2016, capital expenditures decreased to $17.9 million or 2.4% of net sales as compared to $22.6 million or 2.9% of net sales in the prior year. &nbsp;We anticipated 2016 capital spending to be approximately $24 million, however due to project delays, spending was $8 million below our target. &nbsp;We anticipate capital expenditures in the range of $26.0 million to $28.0 million in 2017, which includes amounts not spent in 2016. The 2017 capital spending will be focused on completion of the new Engineering Technologies facility in Wisconsin along with growth, cost reduction, and typical maintenance capital programs. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Backlog
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Backlog includes all active or open orders for goods and services that have a firm fixed customer purchase order with defined delivery dates. &nbsp;Backlog also includes any future deliveries based on executed customer contracts, so long as such deliveries are based on agreed upon delivery schedules. &nbsp;Backlog is not generally a significant factor in the Company&#146;s businesses because of our relatively short delivery periods and rapid inventory turnover with the exception of Engineering Technologies. &nbsp;Due to the nature of long term agreements in the Engineering Technologies segment, the timing of orders and delivery dates can vary considerably resulting in significant backlog changes from one period to another.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Backlog orders in place at June 30, 2016 and 2015 are as follows (in thousands): &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Backlog realizable within one year decreased $5.3 million, or 3.1%, to $162.9 million at June 30, 2016 from $168.2 million at June 30, 2015. The backlog decrease of $8.9 million in the Food Service Equipment segment resulted primarily from lower demand in the refrigeration markets. &nbsp;The increase in Electronics backlog of $6.3 million is primarily a result of the recently acquired Northlake business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales for fiscal year 2016 decreased $26.8 million, or 6.6% when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The reduction was primarily in the Refrigeration Solutions group where sales decreased by 12.2%. &nbsp;Three factors contributed to the Refrigeration sales decline: (i) loss of market share into the dollar store market, (ii) reduced sales to major chains due to reduced capital spending, and (iii) reduced sales in Canada due to the strength of the U.S. dollar. &nbsp;We anticipate that capital spending by our major chain customers will remain soft into the first half of fiscal year 2017 but will begin to increase in the second half of fiscal year 2017. &nbsp;Sales from the Cooking Solutions group increased, by 0.5% year over year due to growth in sales to retail supermarkets. &nbsp;Specialty Solutions sales decreased 1.1% as our European pump business was impacted by a weak Euro early in the year. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales for fiscal year 2015 increased $30.9 million, or 8.2%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The sales growth was driven by organic sales increases of 4.9%, sales increases of 3.9% due to our acquisition of Ultrafyer, partially offset by foreign exchange declines. &nbsp;The Refrigerated Solutions group sales increased 4.7% as the group saw a return of the drug retail business in 2015 and strong sales into the dollar store market. &nbsp;This strength was partially offset by weakness in national food service chains. &nbsp;Sales from the Cooking Solutions group increased, by 22.2% year over year. &nbsp;Excluding the Ultrafryer acquisition, Cooking Solutions group sales grew at 4.2% as compared to 2014. Growth was driven by increased spending by U.S. retail supermarket customers. &nbsp;Specialty Solutions sales increased 1.1% as our European pump business was impacted by the weakening of the Euro during the year. &nbsp;Foreign exchange losses in the group were offset by sales growth in our specialty merchandising business as several new chains have signed on for development of customized solutions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations for fiscal year 2016 increased $2.7 million, or 7.2%, when compared to the prior year, and operating income margin grew from 9.2% to 10.5%, up 130 basis points. &nbsp;Operating efficiencies, portfolio focus, paring of low-margin products and expense controls have increased our leverage and have positively impacted income from operations for the segment. &nbsp;Our focus in fiscal year 2017 is to generate positive operating income growth through product rationalization, sales volume increases and margin improvement through future deployment of Standex Operational Excellence.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations for fiscal year 2015 decreased $0.7 million, or 2.0%, when compared to the prior year, and operating income margin declined from 10.1% to 9.2%. &nbsp;The positive impact of the year-over-year volume increase was offset by a combination of adverse market channel, product and customer mix changes; negative foreign exchange impacts and disruptions resulting from a factory closure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales for fiscal year 2016 increased by $13.3 million or 12.0%, compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Sales growth excluding foreign exchange losses of $8.7 million is driven by sales gains at Mold-Tech for new automotive model introductions along with market share gains throughout the world. &nbsp;The Engraving segment also experienced sales gains in its Roll Plate and Machinery business and core forming tooling business. &nbsp;We expect moderate Mold-Tech sales growth in 2017 as new automotive model launches occur in the coming year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Subsequent to our fiscal 2016 year-end, the Company sold its U.S. Roll Plate and Machinery business as it was not strategic and did not meet our growth and return expectations. &nbsp;&nbsp;This divestiture also allows the Company&#146;s management to focus on higher growth and better return businesses within the Engraving segment. &nbsp;In preparation of this sale, during the fourth quarter of 2016, we recorded a $7.3 million non-cash loss to adjust the net assets of this business to their net realizable value. &nbsp;This expense is recorded as a component of Other Operating Income (Expense), net.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Roll Plate and Machinery business sales increased in fiscal 2016 by $2.8 million up to $17.4 million. &nbsp;The sales (in millions) for the Roll Plate and Machinery business from the first to the fourth quarter of fiscal year 2016 were $4.2, $4.9, $4.0, and $4.3, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales for fiscal year 2015 increased by $1.5 million or 1.4%, compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Unfavorable foreign exchange impacted sales $7.2 million. &nbsp;Sales growth excluding foreign exchange losses were primarily driven by continued expansion of our Asia Pacific Mold-Tech business as a result of increased market share. &nbsp;North American sales volumes were down for the year due to lower new automotive model activity and some automotive projects that were pushed out from the fourth quarter to the first half of 2016. &nbsp;Sales of core forming tooling grew 25% or $2.4 million as compared to prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in fiscal year 2016 increased by $5.3 million, or 22%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The operating income improvement is driven by increased volume in all regions, partially offset by unfavorable foreign exchange and market declines in South America. &nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Roll Plate and Machinery business operating income increased in fiscal 2016 by $1.1 million up to $1.2 million. &nbsp;&nbsp;The operating income (in thousands) for the Roll Plate and Machinery business from the first to the fourth quarter of fiscal year 2016 were $89, $242, $378, and $493, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in fiscal year 2015 increased by $2.1 million, or 9.5%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The increase is driven by increased volume in Asia Pacific partially offset by unfavorable foreign exchange and fewer new model launches which impeded margin growth in the mold texturing business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales in the fiscal year 2016 decreased $14.8 million or 15.2% when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Sales distribution by market in 2016 was as follows: 46% aviation, &nbsp;27% space, 10% oil and gas, 8% medical, 9% other markets. &nbsp;Sales in the land based gas turbine and oil and gas markets were down over 60% from the prior year level. The decline was a result of reduced demand in the oil and gas industry due to lower oil prices. &nbsp;We expect this market to remain soft for an extended period of time and have and will continue to reduce costs to align with demand. &nbsp;Total space sales decreased by 20.5% due to the completion of project based contracts in the manned space market. Sales in the unmanned space market were up 18.0% compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Aviation sales increased 29.7% from the prior year due to strong customer demand and recent contract awards. &nbsp;We anticipate that aviation sales will continue to increase during 2017 and will be approximately 50% of the segment&#146;s sales for the year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales in the fiscal year 2015 increased $17.4 million, or 21.8%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Acquisitions contributed $22.5 million or 28.3%, partially offset by organic sales declines of $4.6 million, or 5.8%. &nbsp;Sales in the land based gas turbine and oil and gas markets were down 24.9% from the prior year level. &nbsp;The decline was a result of reduced demand due to lower oil prices. &nbsp;Space market sales increased 26.3% from the prior year driven by higher sales in both the launch vehicle and the manned space market currently in the development phase. &nbsp;Legacy sales in the aviation market were up 24% compared to the prior year due to recent contract awards. &nbsp;Defense related sales were down 41.2% due to the timing of project based contracts. &nbsp;Sales in the medical market were down 14.4% primarily due to a shift in product mix.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in the fiscal year 2016 decreased $4.8 million or 36.9% when compared to the prior year. Operating income results were negatively impacted by the significant sales declines in both the energy and oil and gas related markets. This impact was partially offset by improved margins in the aviation market along with cost reduction programs implemented as a result of lower volume. &nbsp;We expect that our new Aluminum Center of Excellence facility will be fully operational beginning in the first quarter of 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in the fiscal year 2015 increased $0.4 million, or 3.3%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Operating income was negatively impacted by $1.1 million of purchase accounting expenses associated with the Enginetics acquisition and lower volume from oil and gas customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

	Electronics

</B>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales in the fiscal year 2016 increased $4.1 million, 3.6%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Organic sales growth was $0.7 million, or 0.6%, while the Northlake acquisition contributed $7.5 million. &nbsp;Foreign exchange rates adversely affected sales by $4.1 million. &nbsp;Sales growth in local currency was particularly strong in Europe driven by volume increases in the sensor components. &nbsp;We experienced sales declines in both Asia and North America due to general market softness, particularly earlier in the fiscal year. &nbsp;We expect North American and European sales to increase in fiscal year 2017 which will be partially offset by continued weakness in Asia. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales in the fiscal year 2015 decreased $0.7 million, 0.6%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Organic sales growth of $4.8 million or 4.2% were more than offset by exchange rate declines of $6.2 million. &nbsp;Almost all of the growth came from the sensor, relay and planar product lines across all major geographic areas. &nbsp;Sales growth in local currency was particularly strong in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in the fiscal year 2016 increased $0.2 million, or 1.1%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The operating improvements were a result of a facility consolidation into our Northlake site partially offset by $0.4 million of purchase accounting charges associated with the Northlake acquisition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in the fiscal year 2015 increased $1.2 million, or 5.8%, when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The improvement were driven by the organic sales growth; operational improvements; material and labor cost savings; favorable product mix due to increased sensor and relay sales; facility consolidations; and improved efficiencies in our new Mexico facility partially offset by a negative impact due to foreign exchange rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<B>
<I>
	Hydraulics
</I>
</B>
</P>

<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">

<TD WIDTH=70.4 />

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales in fiscal year 2016 increased $3.6 million, or 8.7% compared to the prior year. &nbsp;Sales distribution by market in 2016 was as follows: 40% dump trailer and truck, 22% refuse, 22% after market, 6% export, and 10% other markets. &nbsp;Strong demand in the traditional North American dump trailer and truck markets was the largest contributor for the net sales increase in addition to market share gains experienced in the refuse market. &nbsp;In the first quarter of fiscal year 2017 we will complete the expansion of our Tianjin, China facility in order to support continued global market growth.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net sales in the fiscal year 2015 increased $6.9 million, or 20.0% when compared to the prior year. Diversification of our OEM business into refuse and construction equipment along with strong demand for cylinder requirements in the traditional North American dump truck and trailer markets drove the increase in net sales. &nbsp;The business has focused on delivering custom engineered cylinder solutions to OEM customers, including single and double acting telescopic hydraulic cylinders, hydraulic rod cylinders, and most recently pneumatic cylinders. &nbsp;New applications for these products are being utilized on roll off container handlers, garbage trucks, airline support equipment, lift trucks, and specialty loading equipment. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in the fiscal year 2016 increased $0.9 million or 13.3% when compared to the prior year due to market growth, increased sales volume and cost containment efforts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Income from operations in the fiscal year 2015 increased $1.2 million or 21.3% when compared to the prior year due to increased sales volume and better facility utilization.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Corporate expenses in fiscal year 2016 increased $3.9 million or 18.7% when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The increase is due to increased health care expenses, compensation, and professional services.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Corporate expenses in fiscal year 2015 decreased $5.0 million or 19.2% when compared to the prior year. &nbsp;The decrease is primarily due to the absence of management transition cost of $3.9 million incurred in 2014.&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restructuring expenses during fiscal year 2016 were $4.2 million primarily related to a $1.7 million non-cash charge from the sale of a vacant property and a $0.7 million non-cash charge to discontinue a product line at our Refrigeration Solutions group. &nbsp;We also have taken restructuring actions to downsize a Canadian facility in connection with the Northlake acquisition and have reduced personnel in those of our locations impacted by the slowdown in the oil and gas market.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6.667PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restructuring expense during fiscal year 2015 was $3.4 million compared to $10.1 million the prior year. &nbsp;Restructuring expense consisted of $2.6 million related to facility closures and consolidations in the Food Service Equipment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company anticipates further restructuring charges in 2017 based upon market conditions and cost reduction activities to improve our competitive advantage.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During fiscal year 2016, other operating income (expense), net was primarily due to a non-cash loss of $7.3 million incurred to adjust the net realizable value of the U.S. Roll Plate and Machinery business in preparation for its sale on July&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During fiscal year 2015, other operating income (expense), net decreased by $3.0 million from the prior year. &nbsp;The decrease was primarily a reduction of insurance proceeds received related to the catastrophic failure of a large vertical machining center located at our Engineering Technologies facility in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Discontinued Operations
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In pursuing our business strategy, we have divested certain businesses and recorded activities of these businesses as discontinued operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In June 2014, the Company divested the American Foodservice Company, (&#147;AFS&#148;) a manufacturer of custom design and fabrication of counter systems and cabinets, in our Food Service Equipment segment. &nbsp;In connection with this sale, the Company received proceeds of $3.1 million and recorded a net loss on disposal of $3.2 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	On March 30, 2012, the Air Distribution Products Group, (&#147;ADP&#148;) was sold to a private equity buyer for consideration of $16.1 million consisting of $13.1 million in cash and a $3.0 million promissory note from the buyer. &nbsp;The note was secured by a mortgage on the ADP real estate sold in the transaction in Detroit Lakes, MN, Medina, NY, and Powder Springs, GA. &nbsp;During the first quarter 2016, the private equity buyer of ADP sold one of the facilities securing the note. &nbsp;The Company released all mortgages on the properties and accepted an advanced payment of $2.8 million during October 2015 in order to reduce repayment risk and settle all obligations under the note. &nbsp;The Company recorded a $0.2 million loss in discontinued operations during the first quarter 2016 related to this transaction.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company remained the obligor of ADP&#146;s Philadelphia, PA facility and administrative offices. &nbsp;We have entered into a renewable sublease agreement with a third party for this space. &nbsp;Our total obligation with respect to the lease is $0.7 million, of which $0.3 million was recorded as a liability at June 30, 2016. We do not expect to record additional charges related to these obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During 2014, the Company received notice that its obligations under a guarantee provided to the buyers of ADP were triggered as a result of its withdrawal from both of the multi-employer pension plans in which ADP previously participated.&nbsp; &nbsp;The last of these obligations were settled in July of fiscal year 2016 by a $0.5 million payment to the final multi-employer plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

</P>

	(1)
</I>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT">
<I>
	American Foodservice Company incurred a pretax operational loss of $3.5 million and pretax loss on sale of $4.8 million in 2014.
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At June 30, 2016, our total cash balance was $122.0 million, of which $111.5 million was held by foreign subsidiaries. &nbsp;The repatriation of cash balances from certain of our subsidiaries could have adverse tax consequences or be subject to capital controls; however, those balances are generally available without legal restrictions to fund ordinary business operations. &nbsp;Our current plans are not expected to require a repatriation of cash to fund our U.S. operations and as a result, we intend to indefinitely reinvest our foreign earnings to fund our overseas growth. &nbsp;If the undistributed earnings of our foreign subsidiaries are needed for operations in the United States, we would be required to accrue and pay U.S. taxes upon repatriation. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX">
<B>
	Cash Flow
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net cash provided by operating activities from continuing operations for the year ended June 30, 2016 was $81.2 million, compared to $66.2 million for the same period in 2015. &nbsp;Changes to net cash provided by operating activities of $15.1 million primarily related to net working capital changes of $17.8 million between periods. &nbsp;Net cash used in investing activities from continuing operations for the year ended June 30, 2016 was $31.6 million, consisting primarily of $17.9 million for capital expenditure and $13.7 million to acquire Northlake Engineering, Inc. &nbsp;Net cash used by financing activities for continuing operations for the year ended June 30, 2016, was $20.7 million consisting of debt repayments of $10.0 million, cash dividends of $6.8 million, and repurchased treasury stock of $5.6 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Net cash provided by operating activities from continuing operations for the year ended June 30, 2015 was $66.2 million, compared to $72.0 million for the same period in 2014. &nbsp;Changes to net cash provided by operating activities of $5.8 million primarily related to increases to net income of $5.5 million and $2.9 million of decreases to non-cash stock compensation expenses which were more than offset by the use of cash for net working capital needs during the year. &nbsp;Net cash used in investing activities from continuing operations for the year ended June 30, 2015 was $78.5 million, consisting primarily of $57.1 million for the acquisitions and $22.6 million for capital expenditures. &nbsp;Net cash provided by financing activities for continuing operations for the year ended June 30, 2015, was $44.6 million consisting of net borrowings of $58.0 million primarily related to acquisitions during the year, partially offset by dividends paid of $5.8 million, and repurchased treasury stock of $10.4million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Capital Structure
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During fiscal year 2015, the Company entered into an Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (&#147;Credit Facility&#148;, or &#147;facility&#148;). &nbsp;This five-year Credit Facility expires in December 2019 and has a borrowing limit of $400 million, which can be increased by an amount of up to $100 million, in accordance with specified conditions contained in the agreement. &nbsp;The facility also includes a $10 million sublimit for swing line loans and a $30 million sublimit for letters of credit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Under the terms of the Credit Facility, we will pay a variable rate of interest and a commitment fee on borrowed amounts as well as a commitment fee on unused amounts under the facility. &nbsp;The amount of the commitment fee will depend upon both the undrawn amount remaining available under the facility and the Company&#146;s funded debt to EBITDA (as defined in the agreement) ratio at the last day of each quarter. &nbsp;As our funded debt to EBITDA ratio increases, the commitment fee will increase. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Funds borrowed under the facility may be used for the repayment of debt, working capital, capital expenditures, acquisitions (so long as certain conditions, including a specified funded debt to EBITDA leverage ratio is maintained), and other general corporate purposes. &nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, the Company has used $7.7 million against the letter of credit sub-facility and had the ability to borrow $254.4 million under the facility based on our current EBITDA. &nbsp;The facility contains customary representations, warranties and restrictive covenants, as well as specific financial covenants. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s current financial covenants under the facility are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Interest Coverage Ratio
</I>
	- The Company is required to maintain a ratio of Earnings Before Interest and Taxes, as Adjusted (&#147;Adjusted EBIT per the Credit Facility&#148;), to interest expense for the trailing twelve months of at least 3.0:1. &nbsp;Adjusted EBIT per the Credit Facility specifically excludes extraordinary and certain other defined items such as cash restructuring and acquisition-related charges up to $7.5 million, and unlimited non-cash charges including gains or losses on sale of property and goodwill adjustments. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016, the Company&#146;s Interest Coverage Ratio was 28.76:1.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Leverage Ratio
</I>
	- The Company&#146;s ratio of funded debt to trailing twelve month Adjusted EBITDA per the facility, calculated as Adjusted EBIT per the Credit Facility plus depreciation and amortization, may not exceed 3.5:1. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016, the Company&#146;s Leverage Ratio was 1.01:1.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As of June 30, 2016, we had borrowings under our facility of $93.0 million and the effective rate of interest for outstanding borrowings under the facility was 1.76%. &nbsp;Our primary cash requirements in addition to day-to-day operating needs include interest payments, capital expenditures, acquisitions, share repurchases, and dividends. &nbsp;Our primary sources of cash for these requirements are cash flows from continuing operations and borrowings under the facility. &nbsp;We expect to spend between $26.0 and $28.0 million on capital expenditures during 2017, and expect that depreciation and amortization expense will be between $18.0 and $19.0 million and $3.0 and $4.0 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In order to manage our interest rate exposure, at June 30, 2016 we are party to $50.0 million of active floating to fixed rate swaps. &nbsp;These swaps convert our interest payments from LIBOR to a weighted average rate of 1.43%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Stockholders&#146; equity increased year over year by $21.4 million, primarily as a result of current year net income of $52.1 million partially offset by $11.3 million of unfavorable foreign currency translation, $6.8 million dividends paid, $13.4 million of unrealized pension loss. &nbsp;The Company's net (cash) debt to capital percentage changed to (8.8%) net cash to capital for the year ended June 30, 2016 from 1.6% net debt to capital for the year ended June 30, 2015. &nbsp;The change in net debt to capital is primarily driven by a reduction in borrowings and cash generated through operations. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We sponsor five defined benefit plans including two in the U.S. and one in Germany, U.K. and Ireland.&nbsp; The Company&#146;s pension plan is frozen for U.S. employees and participants in the plan ceased accruing future benefits. &nbsp;The fair value of the Company's U.S. pension plan assets was $197.9 million at June 30, 2016 and the projected benefit obligation in the U.S. was $269.2 million at that time.&nbsp; As a result of past contributions, the plan is not expected to be 100% funded under ERISA rules at June 30, 2016, but we do not expect to make mandatory contributions to the plan until 2018.&nbsp; We expect to pay $1.4 million in prescribed contributions to our U.K. defined benefit plan and other unfunded defined benefit plans in both the U.S. and Europe during fiscal year 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We have evaluated the current and long-term cash requirements of our defined benefit and defined contribution plans as of June 30, 2016 and determined our operating cash flows from continuing operations and available liquidity are expected to be sufficient to cover the required contributions under ERISA and other governing regulations. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We have an insurance program in place to fund supplemental retirement income benefits for six retired executives. &nbsp;Current executives and new hires are not eligible for this program. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016 the underlying policies had a cash surrender value of $19.5 million and are reported net of loans of $10.2 million for which we have the legal right of offset.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

	Contractual obligations of the Company as of June 30, 2016 are as follows (in thousands):
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; WIDTH:72PX; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">

	(2)
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:72PX; PADDING-RIGHT:49.933PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Post-retirement benefits and pension plan contribution payments represents&#146; future pension payments to comply with local funding requirements. &nbsp;Our policy is to fund domestic pension liabilities in accordance with the minimum and maximum limits imposed by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (&#147;ERISA&#148;), federal income tax laws and the funding requirements of the Pension Protection Act of 2006.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At June 30, 2016, we had $2.5 million of non-current liabilities for uncertain tax positions. &nbsp;We are not able to provide a reasonable estimate of the timing of future payments related to these obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Off Balance Sheet Items
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In March 2012, the Company sold substantially all of the assets of the ADP business. &nbsp;In connection with the divestiture, the Company remained the obligor of ADP&#146;s Philadelphia, PA facility and administrative offices. &nbsp;On February 4, 2015 we entered into a one year renewable, sublease agreement for this building. &nbsp;Our total obligation with respect to the remaining Philadelphia leases is $0.7 million, of which $0.3 million was recorded as a liability at June 30, 2016. &nbsp;We do not expect to record additional charges related to these obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At June 30, 2016, and 2015, the Company had standby letters of credit outstanding, primarily for insurance and trade financing purposes, of $7.7 million and $7.2 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We had no other material off balance sheet items at June 30, 2016, other than the operating leases summarized above in the &#147;Contractual obligations&#148; table.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Other Matters
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Inflation &#150;
</I>
	Certain of our expenses, such as wages and benefits, occupancy costs and equipment repair and replacement, are subject to normal inflationary pressures. &nbsp;Inflation for medical costs can impact both our reserves for self-insured medical plans as well as our reserves for workers' compensation claims. &nbsp;We monitor the inflationary rate and make adjustments to reserves whenever it is deemed necessary. &nbsp;Our ability to manage medical costs inflation is dependent upon our ability to manage claims and purchase insurance coverage to limit the maximum exposure for us. &nbsp;Each of our segments is subject to the effects of changing raw material costs caused by the underlying commodity price movements. &nbsp;In general, we do not enter into purchase contracts that extend beyond one operating cycle. &nbsp;While Standex considers our relationship with our suppliers to be good, there can be no assurances that we will not experience any supply shortage.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Foreign Currency Translation &#150;
</I>
	Our primary functional currencies used by our non-U.S. subsidiaries are the Euro, British Pound Sterling (Pound), Mexican (Peso), and Chinese (Yuan). &nbsp;During the current year, the Pound, Euro, Peso and Yuan all decreased in value related to the U.S. Dollar, our reporting currency. &nbsp;Since June&nbsp;30, 2015 the Pound, Euro, Peso, and Yuan have depreciated by 15.3%, 0.3%, 17.6%, and 6.5% respectively (all relative to the U.S. Dollar). &nbsp;These exchange values were used in translating the appropriate non-U.S. subsidiaries&#146; balance sheets into U.S. Dollars at the end of the current year. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Defined Benefit Pension Plans
</I>
	&#150; We record expenses related to these plans based upon various actuarial assumptions such as discount rates and assumed rates of returns. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s pension plan was frozen for substantially all remaining eligible U.S. employees in 2015 and participants in the plan ceased accruing future benefits. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Environmental Matters
</I>
<I>
	&#150;
</I>
	To the best of our knowledge, we believe that we are presently in substantial compliance with all existing applicable environmental laws and regulations and do not anticipate any instances of non-compliance that will have a material effect on our future capital expenditures, earnings or competitive position.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Seasonality
</I>
	&#150; We are a diversified business with generally low levels of seasonality, however our fiscal third quarter is typically the period with the lowest level of activity.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK80">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK79">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Employee Relations
</I>
	&#150; The Company has labor agreements with a number of union locals in the United States and a number of European employees belong to European trade unions. &nbsp;There are two union contracts in the U.S. expiring during fiscal year 2017. &nbsp;The first has been successfully negotiated in July of 2016 and the second will not expire until October 2016. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Critical Accounting Policies
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Consolidated Financial Statements include accounts of the Company and all of our subsidiaries. &nbsp;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America requires us to make estimates and assumptions in certain circumstances that affect amounts reported in the accompanying Consolidated Financial Statements. &nbsp;Although, we believe that materially different amounts would not be reported due to the accounting policies described below, the application of these accounting policies involves the exercise of judgment and use of assumptions as to future uncertainties and, as a result, actual results could differ from these estimates. &nbsp;We have listed a number of accounting policies which we believe to be the most critical. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company&#146;s product sales are recorded when persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, delivery has occurred, the price to the buyer is fixed or determinable, and collectability is reasonably assured. For products that include installation, and if the installation meets the criteria to be considered a separate element, product revenue is recognized upon delivery, and installation revenue is recognized when the installation is complete. &nbsp;Revenues under certain fixed price contracts are generally recorded when deliveries are made.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Sales and estimated profits under certain long-term contracts are recognized under the percentage-of-completion methods of accounting, whereby profits are recorded pro rata, based upon current estimates of costs to complete such contracts. &nbsp;Losses on contracts are provided for in the period in which the losses become determinable. &nbsp;Revisions in profit estimates are reflected on a cumulative basis in the period in which the basis for such revision becomes known. &nbsp;Any excess of the billings over cost and estimated earnings on long-term contracts is included in deferred revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Collectability of Accounts Receivable &#150; Accounts Receivable are reduced by an allowance for amounts that may become uncollectible in the future. &nbsp;Our estimate for the allowance for doubtful accounts related to trade receivables includes evaluation of specific accounts where we have information that the customer may have an inability to meet its financial obligation together with a general provision for unknown but existing doubtful accounts. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Realizability of Inventories &#150; Inventories are valued at the lower of cost or market. &nbsp;The Company regularly reviews inventory values on hand using specific aging categories, and records a provision for obsolete and excess inventory based on historical usage and estimated future usage. &nbsp;As actual future demand or market conditions may vary from those projected by management, adjustments to inventory valuations may be required.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Realization of Goodwill - Goodwill and certain indefinite-lived intangible assets are not amortized, but instead are tested for impairment at least annually and more frequently whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the fair value of the asset may be less than its carrying amount of the asset. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s annual test for impairment is performed using a May 31st measurement date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We have identified our reporting units for impairment testing as our eleven operating segments, which are aggregated into our five reporting segments as disclosed in Note 18 &#150; Industry Segment Information. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The test for impairment is a two-step process. &nbsp;The first step compares the carrying amount of the reporting unit to its estimated fair value (Step 1). &nbsp;To the extent that the carrying value of the reporting unit exceeds its estimated fair value, a second step is performed, wherein the reporting unit&#146;s carrying value is compared to the implied fair value (Step 2). To the extent that the carrying value exceeds the implied fair value, impairment exists and must be recognized.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK23">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK24">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As quoted market prices are not available for the Company&#146;s reporting units, the fair value of the reporting units is determined using a discounted cash flow model (income approach). &nbsp;This method uses various assumptions that are specific to each individual reporting unit in order to determine the fair value. &nbsp;In addition, the Company compares the estimated aggregate fair value of its reporting units to its overall market capitalization.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our annual impairment testing at each reporting unit relied on assumptions surrounding general market conditions, short-term growth rates, a terminal growth rate of 2.5%, and detailed management forecasts of future cash flows prepared by the relevant reporting unit. &nbsp;Fair values were determined primarily by discounting estimated future cash flows at a weighted average cost of capital of 10.31%. &nbsp;An increase in the weighted average cost of capital of approximately 200 basis points in the analysis would not result in the identification of any impairments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	While we believe that our estimates of future cash flows are reasonable, changes in assumptions could significantly affect our valuations and result in impairments in the future. &nbsp;The most significant assumption involved in the Company&#146;s determination of fair value is the cash flow projections of each reporting unit. &nbsp;Certain reporting units have been significantly impacted by the current global economic downturn and if the effects of the current global economic environment are protracted or the recovery is slower than we have projected estimates of future cash flows for each reporting unit may be insufficient to support the carrying value of the reporting units, requiring the Company to re-assess its conclusions related to fair value and the recoverability of goodwill.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As a result of our annual assessment, the Company determined that the fair value of the reporting units exceeded their respective carrying values.&nbsp; Therefore, no impairment charges were recorded in connection with our annual assessment during 2016.&nbsp; Subsequent to our annual impairment test, we disposed of $273 thousand of goodwill recorded in the Engraving segment in connection with our sale of the Roll, Plate, and Machinery business.&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Cost of Employee Benefit Plans &#150; We provide a range of benefits to certain retirees, including pensions and some postretirement benefits. &nbsp;We record expenses relating to these plans based upon various actuarial assumptions such as discount rates, assumed rates of return, compensation increases and turnover rates. &nbsp;The expected return on plan assets assumption of 7.10% in the U.S. is based on our expectation of the long-term average rate of return on assets in the pension funds and is reflective of the current and projected asset mix of the funds and considers the historical returns earned on the funds. &nbsp;We have analyzed the rates of return on assets used and determined that these rates are reasonable based on the plans&#146; historical performance relative to the overall markets as well as our current expectations for long-term rates of returns for our pension assets. &nbsp;The U.S. discount rate of 4.0% reflects the current rate at which pension liabilities could be effectively settled at the end of the year. &nbsp;The discount rate is determined by matching our expected benefit payments from a stream of AA- or higher bonds available in the marketplace, adjusted to eliminate the effects of call provisions. &nbsp;We review our actuarial assumptions, including discount rate and expected long-term rate of return on plan assets, on at least an annual basis and make modifications to the assumptions based on current rates and trends when appropriate. &nbsp;Based on information provided by our actuaries and other relevant sources, we believe that our assumptions are reasonable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK28">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK31">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The cost of employee benefit plans includes the selection of assumptions noted above. &nbsp;A twenty-five basis point change in the expected return on plan assets assumptions, holding our discount rate and other assumptions constant, would increase or decrease pension expense by approximately $0.6 million per year. &nbsp;A twenty-five basis point change in our discount rate, holding all other assumptions constant, would have no impact on 2016 pension expense as changes to amortization of net losses would be offset by changes to interest cost. &nbsp;In future years the impact of discount rate changes could yield different sensitivities. &nbsp;See the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements for further information regarding pension plans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Business Combinations - The accounting for business combinations requires estimates and judgments as to expectations for future cash flows of the acquired business and the allocation of those cash flows to identifiable intangible assets in determining the estimated fair values for assets acquired and liabilities assumed. &nbsp;The fair values assigned to tangible and intangible assets acquired and liabilities assumed, are based on management&#146;s estimates and assumptions, as well as other information compiled by management, including valuations that utilize customary valuation procedures and techniques. If the actual results differ from the estimates and judgments used in these fair values, the amounts recorded in the consolidated financial statements could result in a possible impairment of the intangible assets and goodwill, or require acceleration of the amortization expense of finite-lived intangible assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Allocations of the purchase price for acquisitions are based on estimates of the fair value of the net assets acquired and are subject to adjustment upon finalization of the purchase price allocation. During this measurement period, the Company will adjust assets or liabilities if new information is obtained about facts and circumstances that existed as of the acquisition date that, if known, would have resulted in the recognition of those assets and liabilities as of that date. &nbsp;All changes that do not qualify as measurement period adjustments are included in current period earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	See &quot;Item&nbsp;8. Financial Statements and Supplementary Data, Note&nbsp;1. Summary of Accounting Policies&#148; for information regarding the effect of recently issued accounting pronouncements on our consolidated statements of operations, comprehensive income, stockholders&#146; equity, cash flows, and &nbsp;notes for the year ended June 30, 2016.
</P>
