</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Item 7A. &nbsp;Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Risk Management
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We are exposed to market risks from changes in interest rates, commodity prices and changes in foreign currency exchange. &nbsp;To reduce these risks, we selectively use, from time to time, financial instruments and other proactive management techniques. &nbsp;We have internal policies and procedures that place financial instruments under the direction of the Treasurer and restrict all derivative transactions to those intended for hedging purposes only. &nbsp;The use of financial instruments for trading purposes (except for certain investments in connection with the non-qualified defined contribution plan) or speculation is strictly prohibited. &nbsp;The Company has no majority-owned subsidiaries that are excluded from the consolidated financial statements. &nbsp;Further, we have no interests in or relationships with any special purpose entities. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Exchange Risk
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We are exposed to both transactional risk and translation risk associated with exchange rates. &nbsp;The transactional risk is mitigated, in large part, by natural hedges developed with locally denominated debt service on intercompany accounts. &nbsp;We also mitigate certain of our foreign currency exchange rate risks by entering into forward foreign currency contracts from time to time. &nbsp;The contracts are used as a hedge against anticipated foreign cash flows, such as dividend payments, loan payments, and materials purchases, and are not used for trading or speculative purposes. &nbsp;The fair values of the forward foreign currency exchange contracts are sensitive to changes in foreign currency exchange rates, as an adverse change in foreign currency exchange rates from market rates would decrease the fair value of the contracts. &nbsp;However, any such losses or gains would generally be offset by corresponding gains and losses, respectively, on the related hedged asset or liability. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016 and 2015, the fair value, in the aggregate, of the Company&#146;s open foreign exchange contracts was $0.1 million and an asset of $0.7 million, respectively. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our primary translation risk is with the Euro, British Pound Sterling, Peso, and Chinese Yuan. &nbsp;A hypothetical 10% appreciation or depreciation of the value of any these foreign currencies to the U.S. Dollar at June 30, 2016, would not result in a material change in our operations, financial position, or cash flows. &nbsp;We do not hedge our translation risk. As a result, fluctuations in currency exchange rates can affect our stockholders&#146; equity.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Interest Rate
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company&#146;s effective rate on variable-rate borrowings under the revolving credit agreement is 1.76% and 1.46% at June 30, 2016 and 2015, respectively. &nbsp;Our interest rate exposure is limited primarily to interest rate changes on our variable rate borrowings. &nbsp;From time to time, we will use interest rate swap agreements to modify our exposure to interest rate movements. &nbsp;We currently have $50.0 million of active floating to fixed rate swaps with terms ranging from one to three years. &nbsp;These swaps convert our interest payments from LIBOR to a weighted average rate of 1.43%. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016 and 2015, the fair value, in the aggregate, of the Company&#146;s interest rate swaps was $1.0 million and $0.6 million, respectively. &nbsp;Due to the impact of the swaps, an increase in interest rates would not materially impact our annual interest expense at June 30, 2016. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Concentration of Credit Risk
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	We have a diversified customer base. &nbsp;As such, the risk associated with concentration of credit risk is inherently minimized. &nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, no one customer accounted for more than 5% of our consolidated outstanding receivables or of our sales.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Commodity Prices
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company is exposed to fluctuating market prices for all commodities used in its manufacturing processes. &nbsp;Each of our segments is subject to the effects of changing raw material costs caused by the underlying commodity price movements. &nbsp;In general, we do not enter into purchase contracts that extend beyond one operating cycle. &nbsp;While Standex considers our relationship with our suppliers to be good, there can be no assurances that we will not experience any supply shortage.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Engineering Technologies, Food Service Equipment, Electronics, and Hydraulics segments are all sensitive to price increases for steel products, other metal commodities and petroleum based products. &nbsp;In the past year, we have experienced price fluctuations for a number of materials including steel, copper wire, other metal commodities, refrigeration components and foam insulation. &nbsp;These materials are some of the key elements in the products manufactured in these segments. &nbsp;Wherever possible, we will implement price increases to offset the impact of changing prices. &nbsp;The ultimate acceptance of these price increases, if implemented, will be impacted by our affected divisions&#146; respective competitors and the timing of their price increases.
</P>
</EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:-24PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<B>
	STANDEX INTERNATIONAL CORPORATION AND SUBSIDIARIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<EFX_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT>
<A NAME="FIS_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<B>
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	1. &nbsp;SUMMARY OF ACCOUNTING POLICIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Basis of Presentation and Consolidation
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Standex International Corporation (&#147;Standex&#148; or the &#147;Company&#148;) is a diversified manufacturing company with operations in the United States, Europe, Asia, Africa, and Latin America. &nbsp;The accompanying consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Standex International Corporation and its subsidiaries and are prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America (&#147;GAAP&#148;). &nbsp;All intercompany accounts and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company considers events or transactions that occur after the balance sheet date, but before the financial statements are issued to provide additional evidence relative to certain estimates or to identify matters that require additional disclosure. &nbsp;We evaluated subsequent events through the date and time our consolidated financial statements were issued. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Accounting Estimates
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The preparation of consolidated financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires the use of estimates, judgments and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets, liabilities, revenues and expenses, and related disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and for the period then ended. &nbsp;Estimates are based on historical experience, actuarial estimates, current conditions and various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances. &nbsp;These estimates form the basis for making judgments about the carrying values of assets and liabilities when they are not readily apparent from other sources. &nbsp;These estimates assist in the identification and assessment of the accounting treatment necessary with respect to commitments and contingencies. &nbsp;Actual results may differ from these estimates under different assumptions or conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Cash and Cash Equivalents
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Cash and cash equivalents include highly liquid investments purchased with a maturity of three months or less. &nbsp;These investments are carried at cost, which approximates fair value. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016 and 2015, the Company&#146;s cash was comprised solely of cash on deposit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK63">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK64">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Trading Securities
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company purchases investments for its non-qualified defined contribution plan for employees who exceed certain thresholds under our traditional 401(k) plan. &nbsp;These investments are classified as trading and reported at fair value. &nbsp;The investments generally consist of mutual funds, are included in other non-current assets and amounted to $2.3 million at June&nbsp;30, 2016 and 2015. &nbsp;Gains and losses on these investments are recorded as other non-operating income (expense), net in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Accounts Receivable Allowances
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company has provided an allowance for doubtful accounts reserve which represents the best estimate of probable loss inherent in the Company&#146;s account receivables portfolio. &nbsp;This estimate is derived from the Company&#146;s knowledge of its end markets, customer base, products, and historical experience.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Inventories
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Inventories are stated at the lower of (first-in, first-out) cost or market. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Long-Lived Assets
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Long-lived assets that are used in operations, excluding goodwill and identifiable intangible assets, are tested for recoverability whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that its carrying amount may not be recoverable. &nbsp;Recognition and measurement of a potential impairment loss is performed on assets grouped with other assets and liabilities at the lowest level where identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities. &nbsp;An impairment loss is the amount by which the carrying amount of a long-lived asset (asset group) exceeds its estimated fair value. &nbsp;Fair value is determined based on discounted cash flows or appraised values, depending upon the nature of the assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_23"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Property, Plant and Equipment
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Property, plant and equipment are reported at cost less accumulated depreciation. &nbsp;Depreciation is recorded on assets over their estimated useful lives, generally using the straight-line method. &nbsp;Lives for property, plant and equipment are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=211.2 />

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Routine maintenance costs are expensed as incurred. &nbsp;Major improvements are capitalized. Major improvements to leased buildings are capitalized as leasehold improvements and depreciated over the lesser of the lease term or the life of the improvement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Routine maintenance costs are expensed as incurred. &nbsp;Major improvements are capitalized. &nbsp;Major improvements to leased buildings are capitalized as leasehold improvements and depreciated over the lesser of the lease term or the life of the improvement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Amortization of computer hardware and software of $0.6 million, $0.5 million, and $0.4 million is included as a component of depreciation expense for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	All business combinations are accounted for using the acquisition method. &nbsp;Goodwill and identifiable intangible assets with indefinite lives, are not amortized, but are reviewed annually for impairment or more frequently if impairment indicators arise. Identifiable intangible assets that are not deemed to have indefinite lives are amortized on an accelerated basis over the following useful lives: &nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Fair Value of Financial Instruments
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The financial instruments, shown below, are presented at fair value. &nbsp;Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. &nbsp;Where available, fair value is based on observable market prices or parameters or derived from such prices or parameters. &nbsp;When observable prices or inputs are not available, valuation models may be applied.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Assets and liabilities recorded at fair value in the consolidated balance sheet are categorized based upon the level of judgment associated with the inputs used to measure their fair values. &nbsp;Hierarchical levels directly related to the amount of subjectivity associated with the inputs to fair valuation of these assets and liabilities and the methodologies used in valuation are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Level 1 &#150; Quoted prices in active markets for identical assets and liabilities. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s deferred compensation plan assets consist of shares in various mutual funds (for the deferred compensation plan, investments are participant-directed) which invest in a broad portfolio of debt and equity securities. &nbsp;These assets are valued based on publicly quoted market prices for the funds&#146; shares as of the balance sheet dates. &nbsp;For pension assets (see Note 17 &#150; Employee Benefit Plans), securities are valued based on quoted market prices for securities held directly by the trust.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Level 2 &#150; Inputs, other than quoted prices in an active market, that are observable either directly or indirectly through correlation with market data. &nbsp;For foreign exchange forward contracts and interest rate swaps, the Company values the instruments based on the market price of instruments with similar terms, which are based on spot and forward rates as of the balance sheet dates. &nbsp;For pension assets held in commingled funds (see Note 17 &#150; Employee Benefit Plans) the Company values investments based on the net asset value of the funds, which are derived from the quoted market prices of the underlying fund holdings.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:'ARIAL'; FONT-SIZE:12PT">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
	The Company has considered the creditworthiness of counterparties in valuing all assets and liabilities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Level 3&#150; Unobservable inputs based upon the Company&#146;s best estimate of what market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	We did not have any transfers of assets and liabilities between Level 1 and Level 2 of the fair value measurement hierarchy at June 30, 2016 and 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable, accounts payable and debt are carried at cost, which approximates fair value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The fair values of our financial instruments at June 30, 2016 and 2015 were (in thousands):
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Concentration of Credit Risk
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company is subject to credit risk through trade receivables and short-term cash investments. &nbsp;Concentration of risk with respect to trade receivables is minimized because of the diversification of our operations, as well as our large customer base and our geographical dispersion. &nbsp;No individual customer accounts for more than 5% of revenues or accounts receivable in the periods presented.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Short-term cash investments are placed with high credit-quality financial institutions. &nbsp;The Company monitors the amount of credit exposure in any one institution or type of investment instrument. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Revenue Recognition
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company&#146;s product sales are recorded when persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, delivery has occurred, the price to the buyer is fixed or determinable, and collectability is reasonably assured. &nbsp;For products that include installation, and if the installation meets the criteria to be considered a separate element, product revenue is recognized upon delivery, and installation revenue is recognized when the installation is complete. &nbsp;Revenues under certain fixed price contracts are generally recorded when deliveries are made.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Sales and estimated profits under certain long-term contracts are recognized under the percentage-of-completion methods of accounting, whereby profits are recorded pro rata, based upon current estimates of costs to complete such contracts. &nbsp;Losses on contracts are provided for in the period in which the losses become determinable. &nbsp;Revisions in profit estimates are reflected on a cumulative basis in the period in which the basis for such revision becomes known. &nbsp;Any excess of the billings over cost and estimated earnings on long-term contracts is included in deferred revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Cost of Goods Sold and Selling, General and Administrative Expenses
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company includes expenses in either cost of goods sold or selling, general and administrative categories based upon the natural classification of the expenses. &nbsp;Cost of goods sold includes expenses associated with the acquisition, inspection, manufacturing and receiving of materials for use in the manufacturing process. &nbsp;These costs include inbound freight charges, purchasing and receiving costs, inspection costs, internal transfer costs as well as depreciation, amortization, wages, benefits and other costs that are incurred directly or indirectly to support the manufacturing process. &nbsp;Selling, general and administrative includes expenses associated with the distribution of our products, sales effort, administration costs and other costs that are not incurred to support the manufacturing process. &nbsp;The Company records distribution costs associated with the sale of inventory as a component of selling, general and administrative expenses in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;These expenses include warehousing costs, outbound freight charges and costs associated with distribution personnel. &nbsp;Our gross profit margins may not be comparable to those of other entities due to different classifications of costs and expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company purchased $3.3 million, $2.1 million, and $1.6 million from a 20% owned equity interest during the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014 respectively.&nbsp; The inventory was purchased under customary terms and conditions and sold to customers in the ordinary course of business.&nbsp; Earning from this investment are not material and are accounted for under the equity method.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our total advertising expenses, which are classified under selling, general, and administrative expenses are primarily related to trade shows, and totaled $4.3 million, $5.0 million, and $4.6 million for the years ended
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11PT">
	June 30
</FONT>
	, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Research and Development
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Research and development expenditures are expensed as incurred. &nbsp;Total research and development costs, which are classified under selling, general, and administrative expenses, were $4.9 million, $4.1 million, and $4.8 million for the years ended
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11PT">
	June&nbsp;30
</FONT>
	, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Warranties
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The expected cost associated with warranty obligations on our products is recorded when the revenue is recognized. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s estimate of warranty cost is based on contract terms and historical warranty loss experience that is periodically adjusted for recent actual experience. &nbsp;Since warranty estimates are forecasts based on the best available information, claims costs may differ from amounts provided. &nbsp;Adjustments to initial obligations for warranties are made as changes in the obligations become reasonably estimable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;6,941
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The increase in warranty expense during 2016 compared to 2015 is primarily due to the introduction of a longer warranty period for sales in our Refrigeration services group. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Stock-Based Compensation Plans
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restricted stock awards generally vest over a three-year period. &nbsp;Compensation expense associated with these awards is recorded based on their grant-date fair values and is generally recognized on a straight-line basis over the vesting period except for awards with performance conditions, which are recognized on a graded vesting schedule. &nbsp;Compensation cost for an award with a performance condition is based on the probable outcome of that performance condition. &nbsp;The stated vesting period is considered non-substantive for retirement eligible participants. &nbsp;Accordingly, the Company recognizes any remaining unrecognized compensation expense upon participant reaching retirement eligibility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Foreign Currency Translation
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The functional currency of our non-U.S. operations is generally the local currency. &nbsp;Assets and liabilities of non-U.S. operations are translated into U.S. Dollars on a monthly basis using period-end exchange rates. &nbsp;Revenues and expenses of these operations are translated using average exchange rates. &nbsp;The resulting translation adjustment is reported as a component of comprehensive income (loss) in the consolidated statements of stockholders&#146; equity and comprehensive income. &nbsp;Gains and losses from foreign currency transactions are included in results of operations and were not material for any period presented.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company recognizes all derivatives on its balance sheet at fair value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Forward foreign currency exchange contracts are periodically used to limit the impact of currency fluctuations on certain anticipated foreign cash flows, such as foreign purchases of materials and loan payments from subsidiaries. &nbsp;The Company enters into such contracts for hedging purposes only. &nbsp;For hedges of intercompany loan payments, the Company records derivative gains and losses directly to the statement of operations due to the general short-term nature and predictability of the transactions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company also uses interest rate swaps to manage exposure to interest rates on the Company&#146;s variable rate indebtedness. &nbsp;The Company values the swaps based on contract prices in the derivatives market for similar instruments. &nbsp;The Company has designated the swaps as cash flow hedges, and changes in the fair value of the swaps are recognized in other comprehensive income (loss) until the hedged items are recognized in earnings. &nbsp;Hedge ineffectiveness, if any, associated with the swaps will be reported by the Company in interest expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company does not hold or issue derivative instruments for trading purposes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Deferred assets and liabilities are recorded for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements or tax returns. &nbsp;Deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and the tax bases of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates. &nbsp;Valuation allowances are provided when the Company does not believe it more likely than not the benefit of identified tax assets will be realized.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company provides reserves for potential payments of tax to various tax authorities related to uncertain tax positions and other issues. &nbsp;The Company accounts for uncertain tax positions based on a determination of whether and how much of a tax benefit taken by the Company in its tax filings or positions is more likely than not to be realized following resolution of any potential contingencies present related to the tax benefit, assuming that the matter in question will be raised by the tax authorities. &nbsp;Interest and penalties associated with such uncertain tax positions are recorded as a component of income tax expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Both basic and dilutive income is the same for computing earnings per share. &nbsp;There were no outstanding instruments that had an anti-dilutive effect at June 30, 2016, 2015 and 2014.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In May&nbsp;2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;) and the International Accounting Standards Board jointly issued a comprehensive new revenue recognition standard, ASU 2014-09,
<I>
	Revenue from Contract with Customers,
</I>
	that will supersede nearly all existing revenue recognition guidance under US GAAP and IFRS. &nbsp;The standard&#146;s primary principle is that a company will recognize revenue when it transfers promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the Company expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&nbsp; The original standard was effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2016; however, in July 2015, the FASB approved a one-year deferral of this standard, with a new effective date for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2017. &nbsp;We expect to adopt this standard in the quarter ending September 30, 2018. &nbsp;The Company is continuing to evaluate the impact of adopting ASU 2014-09 on its consolidated financial statements
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In April 2015, the FASB issued accounting standard update ASU 2015-3,
<I>
	Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Cost.
</I>
	&nbsp;The standard is effective for annual and interim periods with those annual periods beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2015.&nbsp; Early adoption is permitted and retrospective application is required. &nbsp;We adopted this standard in the quarter ended September 30, 2015. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s adoption of ASU 2015-3 has been completed and is reflected herein by the reclass of debt issuance cost from Other non-current assets to Long-term debt.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-11,
<I>
	Inventory (Topic 330): Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory
</I>
	. &nbsp;The standard is effective for annual and interim periods with those annual periods beginning after December 15, 2016. The amendment is to be applied prospectively. &nbsp;The Company is continuing to evaluate the impact of adopting ASU 2015-11 but currently we do not expect the adoption to have a material impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In September 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-16,
<I>
	Business Combination (Topic 805): Simplifying the Accounting for Measurement Period Adjustments
</I>
	. &nbsp;The Standard is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2015, including interim periods within those fiscal years. &nbsp;The amendments of this standard will not materially impact the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In November 2015, the FASB issued ASC Update 2015-17,
<I>
	Income Taxes (Topic 740): Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred Taxes
</I>
	, as part of its simplification initiatives. This update requires deferred tax liabilities and assets to be classified as non-current on the consolidated condensed balance sheet for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2016, and interim periods within those annual periods. Early application is permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;An entity can elect adoption prospectively or retrospectively to all periods presented. &nbsp;The Company is continuing to evaluate the impact of adopting ASU 2015-17.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In January 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-01,
<I>
	Financial Instruments - Overall (Subtopic 825-10): Recognition and measurement of financial assets and financial liabilities.
</I>
	&nbsp;ASU 2016-01 addresses certain aspects of recognition, measurement, presentation and disclosure of financial instruments. This standard is effective for annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2017 and interim periods within those fiscal years and early application is permitted. &nbsp;The adoption of this standard is not expected to have a material impact on the financial position or results of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In February 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-02,
<I>
	Leases (Topic 842)
</I>
	. &nbsp;ASU 2016-02 increases transparency and comparability among organizations by recognizing lease assets and liabilities on the balance sheet and disclosing key information about leasing arrangements. &nbsp;For leases with a term or twelve months or less, a lessee is permitted to make an accounting policy election by class of underlying asset not to recognize lease assets and liabilities. &nbsp;ASU 2016-02 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2018. &nbsp;&nbsp;The Company is continuing to evaluate the impact of adopting ASU&nbsp;2016-02. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In March 2016 the FASB issued ASU 2016- 09,
<I>
	Compensation&#151;Stock Compensation (Topic 718): Improvements to Employee Share-Based Payment Accounting
</I>
	. &nbsp;The standard is applied effective for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2016, and interim periods within those annual periods. &nbsp;The Company is continuing to evaluate the impact of adopting ASU 2016-09.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	2. &nbsp;ACQUISITIONS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company&#146;s recent acquisitions are strategically significant to the future growth prospects of the Company, however at the time of the acquisition and June 30, 2016, we concluded, that historical results of the acquired Companies both individually and in the aggregate, were immaterial to the Company&#146;s consolidated financial results and therefore additional proforma disclosures are not presented. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<U>
	Northlake
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	On October 1, 2015, the Company acquired Northlake Engineering, Inc., (&#147;Northlake&#148;), a Wisconsin-based designer, manufacturer and distributor of high reliability electromagnetic products and solutions serving the North America power distribution and medical equipment markets. &nbsp;Northlake reports to our Electronics segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company paid $13.7 million in cash for 100% of the outstanding stock of Northlake and has recorded intangible assets of $6.8 million, consisting of $4.1 million of customer relationships which primarily are expected to be amortized over a period of twelve and half years, $2.4 million of trademarks which are indefinite-lived and $0.3 million of non-compete which are expected to amortized over a period of five years. &nbsp;Acquired goodwill of $5.1 million is deductible for income tax purposes. &nbsp;The Company finalized the purchase price allocation during the quarter ending June 30, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The components of the fair value of the Northlake acquisition, including the allocation of the purchase price at June 30, 2016, are as follows (in thousands):
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<U>
	Enginetics
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	On September 4, 2014, the Company acquired Enginetics Corporation (&#147;Enginetics&#148;), a leading producer of aircraft engine components for all major aircraft platforms. &nbsp;This investment complements our Engineering Technologies segment and allows us to provide broader solutions to the aviation market.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company paid $55.0 million in cash for 100% of the outstanding stock of MPE Aeroengines, Inc., of which Enginetics is a wholly owned subsidiary and has recorded intangible assets of $10.6 million, consisting of $9.1 million of customer relationships which are expected to be amortized over a period of fifteen years and $1.5 million of trademarks which are indefinite-lived. &nbsp;Acquired goodwill of $34.8 million is not deductible for income tax purposes due to the nature of the transaction. &nbsp;The Company finalized the purchase price allocation during the fourth quarter ended June 30, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The components of the fair value of the Enginetics acquisition, including the allocation of the purchase price at June 30, 2015, are as follows (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<U>
	Ultrafryer
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company paid a total of $23.0 million, in cash, to acquire all of the outstanding stock of Ultrafryer Systems, Inc. (&#147;Ultrafryer&#148;), a producer of commercial deep fryers for restaurant and commercial installations on June 20, 2014. &nbsp;The stock purchase agreement included, a $2.2 million disbursement made in September of fiscal 2015 related to the purchase of land and building associated with the business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Depreciation expense for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014 totaled $13.7 million, $13.4 million, and $12.2 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During the fourth quarter of fiscal year 2015, the Company classified land and buildings valued at $1.9 million, net related to a vacant building that was sold in the first quarter of 2016 as available for sale within other current assets. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK39">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK40">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-1.933PX">
<B>
	5. &nbsp;GOODWILL
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK66">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK65">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK45">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK46">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK19">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Goodwill and certain indefinite-lived intangible assets are not amortized, but instead are tested for impairment at least annually and more frequently whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the fair value of the asset may be less than its carrying amount of the asset. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s annual test for impairment is performed using a May 31st measurement date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company has identified our reporting units for impairment testing as its eleven operating segments, which are aggregated into five reporting segments as disclosed in Note 18 &#150; Industry Segment Information. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As quoted market prices are not available for the Company&#146;s reporting units, the fair value of the reporting units is determined using a discounted cash flow model (income approach). &nbsp;This method uses various assumptions that are specific to each individual reporting unit in order to determine the fair value. &nbsp;In addition, the Company compares the estimated aggregate fair value of its reporting units to its overall market capitalization.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	While the Company believes that estimates of future cash flows are reasonable, changes in assumptions could significantly affect valuations and result in impairments in the future. &nbsp;The most significant assumption involved in the Company&#146;s determination of fair value is the cash flow projections of each reporting unit. &nbsp;If the estimates of future cash flows for each reporting unit may be insufficient to support the carrying value of the reporting units, the Company will reassess its conclusions related to fair value and the recoverability of goodwill.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As a result of our annual assessment, the Company determined that the fair value of the reporting units exceeded their respective carrying values.&nbsp; Therefore, no impairment charges were recorded in connection with its assessments during 2016 and 2015. &nbsp;Subsequent to our annual impairment test, we disposed of $273 thousand of goodwill recorded in the Engraving segment in connection with the July 1, 2016 sale of the Roll, Plate, and Machinery business.&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-1.933PX">
	Changes to goodwill during the years ended June 30, 2016 and 2015 are as follows (in thousands):
</P>

</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Amortization expense from continuing operations for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014 totaled $3.6 million, $2.8 million, and $2.6 million, respectively. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016, aggregate amortization expense is estimated to be $3.8 million in fiscal 2017, $3.5 million in fiscal 2018, $3.2 million in fiscal 2019, $2.8 million in fiscal 2020, $2.3 million in fiscal 2021, and $7.5 million thereafter.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During the fourth quarter of 2016, the Company discontinued a previously acquired product line within the Food Service Equipment Group.&nbsp; As part of this discontinuation, the Company concluded that the trademark value assigned to this product line was no longer realizable and the Company recorded a $600 thousand expense to reduce the trademark to zero.&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-1.933PX">
<B>
<I>
	Bank Credit Agreements
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During fiscal year 2015, the Company entered into an Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (&#147;Credit Facility&#148;, or &#147;facility&#148;). &nbsp;This five-year Credit Facility expires in December 2019 and has a borrowing limit of $400 million, which can be increased by an amount of up to $100 million, in accordance with specified conditions contained in the agreement. &nbsp;The facility also includes a $10 million sublimit for swing line loans and a $30 million sublimit for letters of credit. &nbsp;The facility amends and restates a previously existing $225 million revolving credit agreement, which was scheduled to expire in January 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Under the terms of the Credit Agreement, we will pay a variable rate of interest and a commitment fee on borrowed amounts as well as a commitment fee on unused amounts under the facility. &nbsp;The amount of the commitment fee will depend upon both the undrawn amount remaining available under the facility and the Company&#146;s funded debt to EBITDA (as defined in the agreement) ratio at the last day of each quarter. &nbsp;As our funded debt to EBITDA ratio increases, the commitment fee will increase. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Funds borrowed under the facility may be used for the repayment of debt, working capital, capital expenditures, acquisitions (so long as certain conditions, including a specified funded debt to EBITDA leverage ratio is maintained), and other general corporate purposes. &nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, the Company had the ability to borrow $254.4 million under the facility based on our current EBITDA. &nbsp;The facility contains customary representations, warranties and restrictive covenants, as well as specific financial covenants which the Company was compliant with as of June 30, 2016. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s current financial covenants under the facility are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Interest Coverage Ratio
</I>
	- The Company is required to maintain a ratio of Earnings Before Interest and Taxes, as Adjusted (&#147;Adjusted EBIT per the Credit Agreement&#148;), to interest expense for the trailing twelve months of at least 3.0:1. &nbsp;Adjusted EBIT per the Credit Agreement specifically excludes extraordinary and certain other defined items such as cash restructuring and acquisition-related charges up to $7.5 million, and unlimited non-cash charges including gains or losses on sale of property and goodwill adjustments. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016, the Company&#146;s Interest Coverage Ratio was 28.76:1.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Leverage Ratio
</I>
	- The Company&#146;s ratio of funded debt to trailing twelve month Adjusted EBITDA per the credit agreement, calculated as Adjusted EBIT per the Credit Agreement plus depreciation and amortization, may not exceed 3.5:1. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016, the Company&#146;s Leverage Ratio was 1.01:1.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:3.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As of June 30, 2016, we had borrowings under our facility of $93.0 million and the effective rate of interest for outstanding borrowings under the facility was 1.76%. &nbsp;Our primary cash requirements in addition to day-to-day operating needs include interest payments, capital expenditures, and dividends. &nbsp;Our primary sources of cash for these requirements are cash flows from continuing operations and borrowings under the facility. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In order to manage our interest rate exposure, we are party to $50.0 million of active floating to fixed rate swaps. &nbsp;These swaps convert our interest payments from LIBOR to a weighted average rate of 1.43%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-1.933PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Other Long-Term Borrowings
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At June 30, 2016, and 2015, the Company had standby letter of credit sub-facility outstanding, primarily for insurance and commercial trade purposes of $7.7 million and $7.2 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:681.6PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company reported no losses for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014, as a result of hedge ineffectiveness. Future changes in these swap arrangements, including termination of the agreements, may result in a reclassification of any gain or loss reported in accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) into earnings as an adjustment to interest expense. &nbsp;Accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) related to these instruments is being amortized into interest expense concurrent with the hedged exposure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Foreign Exchange Contracts
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Forward foreign currency exchange contracts are used to limit the impact of currency fluctuations on certain anticipated foreign cash flows, such as foreign purchases of materials and loan payments to and from subsidiaries. &nbsp;The Company enters into such contracts for hedging purposes only. &nbsp;For hedges of intercompany loan payments, the Company has not elected hedge accounting due to the general short-term nature and predictability of the transactions, and records derivative gains and losses directly to the consolidated statement of operations. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016 and 2015 the Company had outstanding forward contracts related to hedges of intercompany loans with net unrealized gain / (losses) of $(0.1) million and $0.7 million, respectively, which approximate the unrealized gains or losses on the related loans. &nbsp;The contracts have maturity dates ranging from 2017-2019, which correspond to the related intercompany loans. &nbsp;The notional amounts of these instruments, by currency, are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Changes in the effective tax rates from period to period may be significant as they depend on many factors including, but not limited to, size of the Company&#146;s income or loss and any one-time activities occurring during the period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2016 was impacted by the following items: (i) a net benefit of $0.9 million related to a bargain-sale of idle property to a charitable organization, and (ii)&nbsp;a benefit of $0.7 million related to the R&amp;D tax credit, and (iii) a benefit of $4.9 million due to the mix of income earned in jurisdictions with beneficial tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2015 was impacted by the following items: (i) a benefit of $0.5 million related to the R&amp;D tax credit that expired during the fiscal year on December 31, and (ii) a benefit of $4.0 million due to the mix of income earned in jurisdictions with beneficial tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company's income tax provision from continuing operations for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2014 was impacted by the following items: (i) a benefit of $0.5 million related to the R&amp;D tax credit that expired during the fiscal year on December 31, (ii) a benefit of $0.5 million related to a decrease in the statutory tax rate in the United Kingdom on prior period deferred tax liabilities recorded during the first quarter during the fiscal year, (iii) a benefit of $1.1 million due to non-taxable life insurance proceeds received in the third quarter and (iv) a benefit of $3.8 million due to the mix of income earned in jurisdictions with beneficial tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6.667PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company estimates the degree to which deferred tax assets, including net operating loss and credit carry forwards will result in a benefit based on expected profitability by tax jurisdiction and provides a valuation allowance for tax assets and loss carry forwards that it believes will more likely than not go unrealized. &nbsp;The valuation allowance at June 30, 2016 applies to state and foreign loss carry forwards, which management has concluded that it is more likely than not that these tax benefits will not be realized. &nbsp;The increase (decrease) in the valuation allowance from the prior year was less than $0.1 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6.667PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As of June 30, 2016, the Company had gross state net operating loss (&quot;NOL&quot;) and credit carry forwards of approximately $44.0 million and $2.7 million, respectively, which may be available to offset future state income tax liabilities and expire at various dates from 2016 through 2035. &nbsp;In addition, the Company had foreign NOL carry forwards of approximately $2.6 million, $1.3 million of which carry forward indefinitely and $1.3 million that carry forward for 10 years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6.667PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company&#146;s income taxes currently payable for federal and state purposes have been reduced by the benefit of the tax deduction in excess of recognized compensation cost from employee stock compensation transactions. &nbsp;The provision for income taxes that is currently payable has not been adjusted by approximately $2.1 million and $2.1 million of such benefits &nbsp;as they have been allocated to additional paid in capital in 2016 and 2015, respectively. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	A provision has not been made for U.S. or additional non-U.S. taxes on $194.5 million of undistributed earnings of international subsidiaries that could be subject to taxation if remitted to the U.S. &nbsp;It is not practicable to estimate the amount of tax that might be payable on the remaining undistributed earnings. &nbsp;Our intention is to reinvest these earnings permanently or to repatriate the earnings only when it is tax effective to do so. &nbsp;Accordingly, we believe that U.S. tax on any earnings that might be repatriated would be substantially offset by U.S. foreign tax credits.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The total provision for income taxes included in the consolidated financial statements was as follows (in thousands):
</P>

<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK22">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	12. &nbsp;CONTINGENCIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	From time to time, the Company is subject to various claims and legal proceedings, including claims related to environmental remediation, either asserted or unasserted, that arise in the ordinary course of business. &nbsp;While the outcome of these proceedings and claims cannot be predicted with certainty, the Company&#146;s management does not believe that the outcome of any of the currently existing legal matters will have a material impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flow. The Company accrues for losses related to a claim or litigation when the Company&#146;s management considers a potential loss probable and can reasonably estimate such potential loss.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	13. &nbsp;STOCK-BASED COMPENSATION AND PURCHASE PLANS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Stock-Based Compensation Plans
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Under incentive compensation plans, the Company is authorized to make grants of stock options, restricted stock and performance share units to provide equity incentive compensation to key employees and directors. &nbsp;&nbsp;The stock award program offers employees and directors the opportunity to earn shares of our stock over time, rather than options that give the employees and directors the right to purchase stock at a set price. &nbsp;The Company has stock plans for directors, officers and certain key employees. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Total compensation cost recognized in income for equity based compensation awards was $5.1million, $3.8 million, and $6.6 million for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively, primarily within Selling, General, and Administrative Expenses. &nbsp;The total income tax benefit recognized in the consolidated statement of operations for equity-based compensation plans was $1.8 million, $1.3 million, and $2.3 million for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	319,211 shares of common stock were reserved for issuance under various compensation plans at June 30, 2016. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Restricted Stock Awards
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company may award shares of restricted stock to eligible employees and non-employee directors of the Company at no cost, giving them in most instances all of the rights of stockholders, except that they may not sell, assign, pledge or otherwise encumber such shares and rights during the restriction period. &nbsp;Such shares and rights are subject to forfeiture if certain employment conditions are not met. &nbsp;During the restriction period, recipients of the shares are entitled to dividend equivalents on such shares, providing that such shares are not forfeited. &nbsp;Dividends are accumulated and paid out at the end of the restriction period. &nbsp;During 2016, 2015, and 2014, the Company granted 48,984, 43,598, and 62,698 shares, respectively, of restricted stock to eligible participants. &nbsp;Restrictions on the stock awards generally lapse between fiscal 2017 and fiscal 2019. &nbsp;For the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015, and 2014, $2.6 million, $2.3 million, and $3.3 million, respectively, was recognized as compensation expense related to restricted stock awards. &nbsp;Substantially all awards are expected to vest.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	A summary of restricted stock awards activity during the year ended June 30, 2016 is as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restricted stock awards granted during 2016, 2015 and 2014 had a weighted average grant date fair value of $77.38, $76.47, and $58.84, respectively. &nbsp;The grant date fair value of restricted stock awards is determined based on the closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock on the date of grant. &nbsp;The total intrinsic value of awards exercised during the years ended June&nbsp;30,&nbsp;2016, 2015, and 2014 was $1.1million, $2.8 million, and $3.1 million, respectively. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As of June 30, 2016, there was $3.1 million of unrecognized compensation costs related to awards expected to be recognized over a weighted-average period of 1.49 years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Executive Compensation Program
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company operates a compensation program for key employees. &nbsp;The plan contains both an annual component as well as a long-term component. &nbsp;Under the annual component, participants may elect to defer up to 50% of their annual incentive compensation in restricted stock which is purchased at a discount to the market. &nbsp;Additionally, non-employee directors of the Company may defer a portion of their director&#146;s fees in restricted stock units which is purchased at a discount to the market. &nbsp;During the restriction period, recipients of the shares are entitled to dividend equivalents on such units, providing that such shares are not forfeited. &nbsp;Dividend equivalents are accumulated and paid out at the end of the restriction period. &nbsp;The restrictions on the units expire after three years. &nbsp;At June 30, 2016 and 2015, respectively, 30,597 and 43,549 shares of restricted stock units are outstanding and subject to restrictions that lapse between fiscal 2017 and fiscal 2019. &nbsp;The compensation expense associated with this incentive program is charged to income over the restriction period. &nbsp;The Company recorded compensation expense related to this program of $0.2 million, $0.3 million, and $0.7 million for the years ended June&nbsp;30, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	As of June 30, 2016, there was $0.3 million of unrecognized compensation costs related to awards expected to be recognized over a weighted-average period of 1.28 years
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The fair value of the awards under the annual component of this incentive program is measured using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model. &nbsp;Key assumptions used to apply this pricing model are as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Under the long-term component, grants of performance share units (&#147;PSUs&#148;) are made annually to key employees and the share units are earned based on the achievement of certain overall corporate financial performance targets over the performance period. &nbsp;At the end of the performance period, the number of shares of common stock issued will be determined by adjusting upward or downward from the target in a range between 50% and 200%. &nbsp;No shares will be issued if the minimum performance threshold is not achieved. The final performance percentage, on which the payout will be based, considering the performance metrics established for the performance period, will be certified by the Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The awards granted by the Committee provided that the PSUs will be converted to shares of common stock if the Company&#146;s EBITDA (earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization) and return on assets meet specified levels approved by the Committee. &nbsp;A participant&#146;s right to any shares that are earned will vest in three equal installments. &nbsp;An executive whose employment terminates prior to the vesting of any installment for a reason other than death, disability, retirement, or following a change in control, will forfeit the shares represented by that installment. &nbsp;In certain circumstances, such as death, disability, or retirement, PSUs are paid on a pro-rata basis. &nbsp;In the event of a change in control, vesting of the awards granted is accelerated.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

	A summary of the awards activity under the executive compensation program during the year ended June 30, 2016 is as follows:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restricted stock awards granted under the annual component of this program in fiscal 2016, 2015, and 2014 had a grant date fair value of $82.79, $80.98, and $69.47, respectively. &nbsp;The PSUs granted in fiscal 2016, 2015 and 2014 had a grant date fair value of $76.61, $74.82, and $54.48, respectively. &nbsp;The total intrinsic value of awards vested under the executive compensation program during the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015 and 2014 was $2.3 million, $1.5 million, and $2.2 million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company recognized compensation expense related to the PSUs of $2.3 million, $1.3 million, and $2.7 million for the years ended June 30, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively based on the probability of the performance targets being met. &nbsp;The total unrecognized compensation costs related to non-vested performance share units was $1.6 million at June 30, 2016, which is expected to be recognized over a weighted average period of 1.30 years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Employee Stock Purchase Plan
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company has an Employee Stock Purchase Plan that allows employees to purchase shares of common stock of the Company at a discount from the market each quarter. &nbsp;Shares of our stock may be purchased by employees quarterly at 95% of the fair market value on the last day of each quarter. &nbsp;Shares of stock reserved for the plan were 90,679 at June 30, 2016. &nbsp;Shares purchased under this plan aggregated 3,809, 3,382, and 4,473 in 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively, at an average price of $75.66, $74.42, and $58.54, respectively. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:9.5PT">
<B>
	15. &nbsp;
</B>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10PT">
<B>
	DISCONTINUED OPERATIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In pursuing our business strategy, we have divested certain businesses and recorded activities of these businesses as discontinued operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In June 2014, the Company divested the American Foodservice Company, (&#147;AFS&#148;) a manufacturer of custom design and fabrication of counter systems and cabinets, in our Food Service Equipment segment. &nbsp;In connection with this sale, the Company received proceeds of $3.1 million and recorded a net loss on disposal of $3.2 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	On March 30, 2012, Air Distribution Products Group, (&#147;ADP&#148;) was sold to a private equity buyer for consideration of $16.1 million consisting of $13.1 million in cash and a $3.0 million promissory note from the buyer. &nbsp;The note was secured by a mortgage on the ADP real estate sold in the transaction in Detroit Lakes, MN, Medina, NY, and Powder Springs, GA. &nbsp;During the first quarter 2016, the private equity buyer of ADP sold one of the facilities securing the note. &nbsp;The Company released all mortgages on the properties and accepted an advanced payment of $2.8 million during October 2015 in order to reduce repayment risk and settle all obligations under the note. &nbsp;The Company recorded a $0.2 million loss in discontinued operations during the first quarter 2016 related to this transaction.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company remained the obligor of ADP&#146;s Philadelphia, PA facility and administrative offices. &nbsp;We have entered into a renewable sublease agreement with a third party for this space. &nbsp;Our total obligation with respect to the lease is $0.7 million, of which $0.3 million was recorded as a liability at June 30, 2016. &nbsp;We do not expect to record additional charges related to these obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During 2014, the Company received notice that its obligations under a guarantee provided to the buyers of ADP were triggered as a result of its withdrawal from both of the multi-employer pension plans in which ADP previously participated.&nbsp; &nbsp;The last of these obligations were settled in July of fiscal year 2016 by a $0.5 million payment to the final multi-employer plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The following table summarizes the Company&#146;s discontinued operations activity, by operation, for the years ended June 30, (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<I>
	2016 Restructuring Initiatives
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company continues to focus on our efforts to reduce cost and improve productivity across our businesses, particularly through headcount reductions, facility closures, and consolidations. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s 2016 initiatives to date include the movement of manufacturing from a legacy Canadian facility into our newly acquired Northlake facility and a reduction of personnel in those locations impacted by the slowdown in the oil and gas market.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restructuring expenses during fiscal year 2016 were $4.2 million primarily related to a $1.7 million non-cash charge from the sale of a vacant property and a $0.7 million non-cash charge to discontinue a product line at our Refrigeration Solutions group. Restructuring activities related to 2016 initiatives are substantially complete.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company anticipates further restructuring charges in 2017 based upon market conditions and cost reduction activities to improve our competitive advantage.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Activity in the reserves related to 2016 restructuring initiatives is as follows (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Prior Year Initiatives
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company previously announced the closure of our Food Service Equipment U.K. facility and entered into a distribution agreement with a U.K. based partner in order to reduce channel costs and enhance profitability, expand and strengthen our U.K. Food Service Equipment group&#146;s presence for all of our brands.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Restructuring activities related to all prior year initiatives are substantially complete. &nbsp;The cumulative expense related to all activities making up this initiative is expected to be $5.7 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Activity in the reserves related to prior year restructuring initiatives is as follows (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	17. &nbsp;EMPLOYEE BENEFIT PLANS
</B>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK68">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_HTM_OLE_LINK67">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Retirement Plans
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company has defined benefit pension plans covering certain current and former employees both inside and outside of the U.S. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s pension plan for U.S. salaried employees was frozen as of December 31, 2007, and participants in the plan ceased accruing future benefits. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s pension plan for U.S. hourly employees was frozen for substantially all participants as of July 31, 2013, and replaced with a defined contribution benefit plan.&nbsp; During fiscal 2015, the Society of Actuaries released new mortality tables that reflect increased life expectancy over the previous tables. The company incorporated these new tables into the 2015 measurement of its U.S. pension obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Net periodic benefit cost for U.S. and non-U.S. plans included the following components (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The accumulated benefit obligation for all defined benefit pension plans was $310.4 million and $295.0 million at June 30, 2016 and 2015, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The estimated actuarial net loss and prior service benefit for the defined benefit pension plans that will be amortized from accumulated other comprehensive income into net periodic benefit cost over the next fiscal year are $5.8 million and less than $0.1 million, respectively.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our investment policy for the U.S. pension plans targets a range of exposure to the various asset classes. &nbsp;Standex rebalances the portfolio periodically when the allocation is not within the desired range of exposure. &nbsp;The plan seeks to provide returns in excess of the various benchmarks. &nbsp;The benchmarks include the following indices: &nbsp;S&amp;P 500; Citigroup PMI EPAC; Citigroup World Government Bond and Barclays Aggregate Bond. &nbsp;A third party investment consultant tracks the plan&#146;s portfolio relative to the benchmarks and provides quarterly investment reviews which consist of a performance and risk assessment on all investment managers and on the portfolio. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Certain managers within the plan use, or have authorization to use, derivative financial instruments for hedging purposes, the creation of market exposures and management of country and asset allocation exposure. &nbsp;Currency speculation derivatives are strictly prohibited.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
